2. Inside the function, iterate through each element in the array from the first one to the second-last one (excluding the last one).
3. For each pair of adjacent elements, compare them and swap their positions if they are in the wrong order.
4. Repeat step 3 for each pair until no more swaps are needed (i.e., the array is sorted).

Here's the implementation:

```cpp
void bubbleSort(int arr[], int n) {
    bool swapped = true;
    int end = n - 1;

    // Traverse through all array elements
    while (swapped) {
        swapped = false;

        // Last I elements (from 0 to end-1)
        for (int I = 0; I < end; i++) {
            // Swap if the element found is greater than the next element
            if (arr[i] > arr[i+1]) {
                int temp = arr[i];
                arr[i] = arr[i+1];
                arr[i+1] = temp;
                swapped = true;
            }
        }

        // Decrease end by 1
        end--;
    }
}

